### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

Angular has a magnificent template syntax. While it is not imaginative as JSX, the performance benefits make it worth the while.

What Angular Templates limit us to, is a strict dependence on the Angular Compiler. There is no escape hatch to native Javascript; I propose determining a syntax which would make this possible.

Consider how Angular developers have to do double the work to access an application constant, compared to React or Vue developers:

## React

#### app-settings.js
````jsx

export const AppName = 'Sample React App';

````
#### app.jsx
````jsx

import { AppName } from './app-settings.js';

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root'));
root.render(<h1>Hello, world, from { AppName } </h1>);

````

## Angular

#### app-settings.ts
````ts

export const AppName = 'Sample Angular App';

````

#### app.component.ts
````ts
import { AppName } from './app-settings';

@Component({
  standalone: true,
  selector: 'app',
  template: `
  <h1>Hello, world, from {{ AppName }} </h1>
  `
})
export class AppComponent {
  AppName = AppName
}
````

It's that extra binding, AppName = AppName, that can get tedious. 

It also forces dependency injection to be used _everywhere_ in a component. That's great for library development, but sometimes your constants are just your constants. Javascript already gives us a module system for shipping things around - can we remove that final "import it into Angular land" step, and just allow templates to access them directly?



### Proposed solution

Introduce another class of Angular Expression which would be considered a **native expression**. Initially, I propose that we disallow the use of pipes for these expressions, though I'm sure they could be worked back in.

For backwards compatability, a **native expression** would likely need to have `{{{ }}}` as its nomenclature.

# Native Expressions

Native Expressions inject native javascript with minimal transformations into the final Ivy view engine instruction set.

Native Expressions cannot do the following: 
 - Use the `export` keyword
 - Use the `class` keyword
 - Use `const`, `let`, `for`, `while`, or other control flow
 - Use `import()`

Native Expressions can do the following:
 - Use static `import` in the first native expression of an Angular template document
 - Reference component via `this`
 - Call functions (use at your own risk)
 - Access ambient variables in the scope of the template.
 
 
## What are some sample templates which use Native Expressions?


## Raw Expression Sample

#### app-settings.ts
````ts

export const AppName = 'Sample Angular App';

````

#### app.component.ts
````ts
import { AppName } from './app-settings';

@Component({
  standalone: true,
  selector: 'app',
  template: `
  <h1>Hello, world, from {{{ AppName }}} </h1>
  `
})
export class AppComponent {
}
````

#### Demonstrating import from a template.html file
````html
{{{
import { AppName } from './app.constants';
}}}
<h1>Hello world from {{AppName}}!</h1>
````

#### Using native expressions as inputs
````ts

import { AppName } from './app-settings';

@Component({
  template: `
<textarea placeholder="Say Something about {{{ AppName }}}"></textarea>
  `
})
export class SampleComponent {}

````

#### Using native expressions as inputs - square bracket syntax
````html
{{{
import { defaultConnectedPositions } from './app-constants';
}}}
<textarea [placeholder]="{{{ AppName }}}"></textarea>
````

````
#### Using getter functions - no integration with Change Detection!
````html
{{{
import { getAppName } from './app-constants';
}}}
<h1>Hi from {{{ getAppName() }}}></textarea>
````

## How do Native Expressions integrate with Ivy?

### Sample Ivy output - static values.
````
/*
All relevant imports etc. are hoisted here.
*/
import { AppName } from './app.constants';

function (renderFlags, ctx) {
  if (renderFlags & RenderFlags.Create) {
     elementStart(0, 'h1',);
     text(1);
     elementEnd();
  }
  if (renderFlags & RenderFlags.Update) {
    advance(1);
    textInterpolate1('Hello world from ', AppName, '!');
  }
}

````

### Sample Ivy output - using function invocation
````
/*
All relevant imports etc. are hoisted here.
*/
import { getAppName } from './app.constants';

function (renderFlags, ctx) {
  if (renderFlags & RenderFlags.Create) {
     elementStart(0, 'h1',);
     text(1);
     elementEnd();
  }
  if (renderFlags & RenderFlags.Update) {
    advance(1);
    textInterpolate1('Hello world from ', getAppName(), '!');
  }
}

````

### Alternatives considered

We can keep doing things that class-based "Angular Way". I don't have much of a choice - we've invested thousands of hours into the product and Angular is "good enough" that there's no reason to abandon it in a rewrite.

That said - we need to find ways to get Angular out of the way. Maybe something like Native Expressions, allowing raw Javascript to take center stage, would be one way to simplify things.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

service-worker

### Description

When using ignoreSearch=true my Angular app became extremly slow showing image galleries, but only for my Chrome users. I have SAS tokens in the query params, who changes frequently. Unfortunately it is a very old known problem (Ref.: https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=682677). hash for full url are saved in index, so when using ignoreSearch=true, every index needs to be checked, not effective and gives poor performance.

E.g. of datagroup
`"dataGroups": [
    {
        "name": "dynamicResources",
        "urls": [
            "**XXX/**"
        ],
        "cacheConfig": {
            "maxSize": 2000,
            "maxAge": "30d",
            "strategy": "performance"
        },
        "cacheQueryOptions": {
            "ignoreSearch": true
        }
    }
]`

### Proposed solution

Is it possible to create an option which causes the query parameters in urls for data groups to be completely ignored, so they are stored without and retrieved without and we keep the good performance?

### Alternatives considered

If not an option, then a workaround where you can overwrite ngsw-worker.js until Chrome is fixed.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

I propose that a new lexical scope be added to the Angular template syntax - While I don't have a good name, "ambient values" closely captures. what I'm going after.

## Background

Presently, the Angular template language has one lexical scope - The component template. In Angular expressions, we can reference "let-scope" variables, or member properties / components of the containing Component class. If we want to access module level imports, we must access those through careful orchestration with the Dependency Injector.

This decision forces Angular developers to be very explicit about what is accessible to their components. It promotes best practices. But in some circumstances, this aspect of the Angular Template makes it painful for developers and results in a lot of code duplication.




### Proposed solution


## Proposal

I propose that the concept of a Module Scoped "Ambient Value" be added to the Angular Template syntax. "Ambient Values" would work just like any other reference in an Angular Expression, with the only difference being the template value source.

Ambient Values would need to be declared in the Providers array of an NgModule or Standalone Component, and use the existing Dependency Injection system.

````ts

import { ambientValue } from '@angular/core';

@NgModule({
   providers: [
      { 
        provide: ambientValue('foo'),
        useValue: 'FOO'
      }
   ]
})
export class SampleModule {}
````

The exact syntax for declaring an Ambient Value is up for debate - the important piece of course would be the name used for reference in the Angular Templates, and the value to resolve.

The value of an Ambient Value would be resolved once upon the first time rendering a Component - It would have a lifecycle identical to other providers in an Angular Module.


````
<!-- A sample component importing SampleModule -->

<p>The message is {{foo}}</p>

<!-- renders, The message is FOO -->

````


## Problems this solves

For Component Libraries, there are complicated settings that must be developed. One example is the `Overlay` library from `@angular/cdk`. Charting libraries are another example, any component with a complex object or array of objects requiring configuration.

To configure components with complex settings, library authors must either provide an `InjectionToken` and allow consumers to configure behavior, or, provide factory functions and classes expecting consumers to duplicate code at the component typescript level.


````ts
// Two possible solutions for shared configuration of a hypothetical charting library


// Using Inejction Tokens

import { FooThemeConfigToken } from '@foo-charts/foo-charts-ngx';
import { appSpecificFooTheme } from 'app/shared/foo-theme';

@Component({
   selector: 'foo-charts-consumer-1',
   template: `
   <foo-chart>
   </foo-chart>
`,
   providers: [{
     provide: FooThemeConfigToken,
     useValue: appSpecificFooTheme 
   }]
})
export class FooChartsConsumer1Component {}


// Using declaration of config values

import { FooThemeConfigToken } from '@foo-charts/foo-charts-ngx';
import { appSpecificFooTheme } from 'app/shared/foo-theme';

@Component({
   selector: 'foo-charts-consumer-2',
   template: `
   <foo-chart [theme]="fooTheme">
   </foo-chart>
`,
})
export class FooChartsConsumer2Component {
  fooTheme = appSpecificFooTheme;
}

````

In the real world, this looks like "connectedPositionStrategy", or declaring a `trackBy:` function over and over again.

Ambient Values would result in the following solution for this chart library:

````
import { FooThemeConfigToken } from '@foo-charts/foo-charts-ngx';

@Component({
   selector: 'foo-charts-ambient-value-consumer',
   template: `
   <foo-chart [theme]="appFooTheme">
   </foo-chart>
`,
})
export class FooChartsAmbientValueConsumerComponent {
}
````


## Ramifications for state management

If this were to be introduced to Angular, it would change the game for state management. Right now, services must be directly injected into each component; Every application component that wants to get the login status of a user, a shopping cart inventory, etc. must inject `UserService`, `CartService` etc. and then access methods directly.

````ts
// Before Ambient Values
@Component({
   selector: 'store-page',
   template: `
   <div>
      <store-item></store-item>
   </div>
   <div *ngIf="user.loggedIn">
      Welcome back! Your cart is {{cart.status}}
   </div>
`
})
export class StorePage {
   constructor(
     public user: UserService,
     public cart: CartService
   ) {
   }
}

// After Ambient Values (assuming UserService and CartService are ambiently declared as user and cart in a higher module).
@Component({
   selector: 'store-page',
   template: `
   <div>
      <store-item></store-item>
   </div>
   <div *ngIf="user.loggedIn">
      Welcome back! Your cart is {{cart.status}}
   </div>
`
})
export class StorePage {}
````

It is debatable which the best solution is for this; It's likely a terrible idea for shared component libraries, but whether or not it's a poor strategy for particular applications is less clear. 

I can imagine that in a large application development team with varying team-member experience, a Sr. Developer might develop an "AcmeApplicationState" module, providing a common vernacular for Jr. Developers to easily access business logic.


### Alternatives considered

This feature may be declared either too much work, or too dangerous as it could promote bad coding practices. However, I think that on the main it would provide powerful ergonomics for developers and would be an appreciated improvement to Angular. For situations where common functions, queries, themes, and state is shared across an entire application, declaring it once in a Module versus re-declaring it in each component would save developers time, and enforce consistency.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

When providing a Service in a component, `inject()` triggers `NullInjectorError ` when called within `runInContext` : 



```typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'my-app',
  templateUrl: './app.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./app.component.css'],
  providers: [Service],
})
export class AppComponent {
  public constructor(injector: EnvironmentInjector, service: Service) {
    console.log(service); // OK
    console.log(inject(Service)); //OK

    setTimeout(() => {
      injector.runInContext(() => {
        console.log(inject(Service)); //KO
      });
    }, 100);
  }
}
```
This does not happen
* if the service is `providedIn:'root'`
* if the service is provided in the module 


